2005-08-12  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * misc: did forget some more pack() and also found out that I still compiled
    with QT3_SUPPORT enabled which in fact caused to still have some unwanted
    compatibility stuff enabled. Now libmedio should be definitly Qt4 only...

2005-08-11  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * misc: removed the structure aligning "#pragma pack()" usages as they break
    compatibility to the picky SPARC processors which always want to have
    stuff aligned to their natural boundaries. This should fix some strange
    crashes which occurred when running libmedio application on an old Sol8
    machine.

2005-08-05  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * misc: removed the qt3support and ported all still existent Qt3 functionality
    to Qt4. Now libmedio should work fully native with Qt4 by just linking against
    the QtCore library.
  * misc: initial port to Qt4 (still with Qt3Support) and separation of the
    CVS repository into two different branches for Qt3 and Qt4 development.
    (MAIN branch is the Qt4 one)

2005-07-14  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * CECATDirectoryItem.cpp: added check&code to enforce that a writeMatrix() call
    always ensures that full ECAT_BLOCKSIZE data is written. Previously, if a
    user passed a matrix/data size which is not divideable through ECAT_BLOCKSIZE,
    libmedio did exactly write the passed data size and as such violated the
    ECAT standard which defines that ECAT files have to be always a mulitple of
    ECAT_BLOCKSIZE data.

2005-07-06  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * m4/acinclude.m4: added gcc4 to supported GCC compiler versions.

2005-04-08  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * CECAT7MainHeader.cpp: implemented special QDateTime/QDate aware
    methods to deal with the time_t related date&time values specified
    in the ECAT format. These methods should make dealing with all that
    time_t mess a bit better as QDateTime seems not to be fully time_t
    aware as it defines time_t to be unsigned :(
  * m4/acinclude.m4: make configure deal with strangs GCC version strings.

2005-03-17  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * CECATDirectoryItem.cpp: fixed bug in the subHeader identification
    routines which caused that a writeMatrix() did always reset the
    subHeader of a file, even if a writeSubHeader() operation was done
    prior to it.

2005-03-07  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * CECATDirectoryItem.cpp: fixed bug in the writeMatrix(data, subHeader)
    sub methods where the supplied subHeader wasn't correctly written to
    the ECAT file.
  * CECAT7MainHeader.cpp: added Dose_Start_Time and plane number settings to
    default settings of the main Header.
   
2005-03-02  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * misc: added a global operator= method to the MedIOHeader interface and
    made it call a pure virtual protected copyData() method. This way we force 
    classes to implement a proper protected copyData() method which then is
    used to copy data (shallow copy) out of one MedIOHeader object to the
    other one. However, please note that currently not all copy operations
    from one header typ to another one is supported. Especially all the
    Concorde<>ECAT copy implementations are missing.
  
2005-02-25  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * SubHeaders: the way ECAT Subheader were cached was done slightly wrong.
    Now the header should be successfully cached either on a save() or
    writeSubHeader() execution.
  * CECATFile.cpp: fixed bug in the mainHeaderWritten() method where upon an
    already existing mainHeader the data wasn't correctly copied out of it.
    This caused that on a writeMatrix() operation an already written
    mainHeader was abadoned.
  * libmedio.pro.in: added optimization level for the different host types
    found by configure.
  * CECATFile.cpp: fixed bug where upon usage of the IO_WriteOnly mode an
    existing file wasn't overwritten at all and the open() call returned
    false.

2005-02-04  Jens Langner <Jens.Langner@light-speed.de>

  * examples/ecat/ecatcmp: added another small usefull example on how to use
    libmedio to read out an ECAT file. This utility can be quite handy if one
    wants to compare two different ECAT files if they are the same.
    It analyses some main Header, SubHeader and also directory list
    information outputs there differences and also compares the raw matrix
    data of each data item in the ECAT file.
  
